initial_story: bias triangles represent features in stability diagrams of quantum dot (qd)devices, whose occurrence and property analysis are crucial indicators for spinphysics. nevertheless, challenges associated with quality and availability ofdata as well as the subtlety of physical phenomena of interest have hindered anautomatic and bespoke analysis framework, often still relying (in part) onhuman labelling and verification. we introduce a feature extraction frameworkfor bias triangles, built from unsupervised, segmentation-based computer visionmethods, which facilitates the direct identification and quantification ofphysical properties of the former. thereby, the need for human input or largetraining datasets to inform supervised learning approaches is circumvented,while additionally enabling the automation of pixelwise shape and featurelabeling. in particular, we demonstrate that pauli spin blockade (psb)detection can be conducted effectively, efficiently and without any trainingdata as a direct result of this approach.

The analysis of bias triangles in stability diagrams of quantum dot devices is essential for understanding spin physics. However, challenges related to data quality and availability, as well as the complexity of the physical phenomena involved, have made it difficult to develop an automated analysis framework. Human labeling and verification are still necessary in many cases. 

In response to these challenges, we have developed a feature extraction framework for bias triangles using unsupervised, segmentation-based computer vision methods. This framework allows for the direct identification and quantification of the physical properties of bias triangles without the need for human input or large training datasets typically required for supervised learning approaches. 

Through this approach, we are able to automate the labeling of pixelwise shapes and features, making processes such as Pauli spin blockade detection more effective and efficient. This method has shown that it is possible to detect PSB without the need for training data, paving the way for more streamlined and accurate analysis of quantum dot device stability diagrams.

Our new feature extraction framework revolutionizes the analysis of quantum dot devices by eliminating the need for human input and large training datasets. By utilizing unsupervised computer vision methods, we are able to identify and quantify the physical properties of bias triangles with unprecedented accuracy and efficiency. This breakthrough allows for the automation of processes such as Pauli spin blockade detection, making the analysis of stability diagrams more streamlined and reliable than ever before. With this innovative approach, we are paving the way for a new era of quantum dot device research that is both cutting-edge and accessible to researchers of all levels.
